# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aesthetic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aesthetic/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:aesthetic/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:aesthetic/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic properties are features that influence the appeal of objects.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They include aesthetic values, which express positive or negative qualities, such as the contrast between beauty and ugliness.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Philosophers debate whether aesthetic properties have objective existence or depend on the subjective experiences of observers.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] According to a common view, aesthetic experiences are associated with disinterested pleasure detached from practical concerns.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Taste is a subjective sensitivity to aesthetic qualities, and differences in taste can lead to disagreements about aesthetic judgments.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Artworks are artifacts or performances typically created by humans, encompassing diverse forms such as painting, music, dance, architecture, and literature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some definitions focus on their intrinsic aesthetic qualities; others understand art as a socially constructed category.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Art interpretation and criticism seek to identify the meanings of artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Discussions focus on elements such as what an artwork represents, which emotions it expresses, and what the author's underlying intent was.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Many fields of study investigate aesthetic phenomena, examining their roles in ethics, religion, and everyday life, as well as the psychological processes involved in aesthetic experiences.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Comparative aesthetics analyzes the similarities and differences between traditions such as Western, Indian, Chinese, Islamic, and African aesthetics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic thought has its roots in antiquity but only emerged as a distinct field of inquiry in the 18th century when philosophers systematically engaged with the subject.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetics, sometimes spelled *esthetics*, is the systematic study of beauty, art, and taste.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] As a branch of philosophy, it examines which types of aesthetic phenomena there are, how people experience them, and how objects evoke them.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This field also investigates the nature of aesthetic judgments, the meaning of artworks, and the problem of art criticism.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Key questions in aesthetics include "What is art?", "Can aesthetic judgments be objective?", and "How is aesthetic value related to other values?".
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One characterization distinguishes between three main approaches to aesthetics: the study of aesthetic concepts and judgments, the study of aesthetic experiences and other mental responses, and the study of the nature and features of aesthetic objects.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] In a slightly different sense, the term *aesthetics* can also refer to particular theories of beauty or to beautiful appearances.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetics is closely related to the philosophy of art, and the two terms are often used interchangeably since both involve the philosophical study of aesthetic phenomena.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One difference is that the philosophy of art focuses on art, whereas the scope of aesthetics also includes other domains, such as beauty in nature and everyday life.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Accordingly, one outlook argues that the philosophy of art is a subfield of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The precise relation between the two fields is disputed, and another characterization holds that the philosophy of art is the broader discipline.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This view asserts that aesthetics mainly addresses aesthetic properties, while the philosophy of art also investigates non-aesthetic features of artworks, belonging to fields such as metaphysics, epistemology, philosophy of language, and ethics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Even though the philosophical study of aesthetic problems originated in antiquity, it was not until the 18th century that aesthetics emerged as a distinct branch of philosophy when philosophers engaged in systematic inquiry into its principles.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The Latin term *aesthetica* was coined by the philosopher Alexander Baumgarten in 1735, initially defined as the study of sensibility or sensations of beautiful objects.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The term comes from the ancient Greek words *aisthetikos*, meaning 'perceptible things', *aisthesthai*, meaning 'perceive, see', and *aisthesis*, meaning 'sensation, perception'.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The earliest known use in the English language appeared in a translation by W.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Philosophers rely on several basic concepts in their inquiry.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They examine aesthetic objects and the properties or features responsible for their appeal, such as beauty.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Researchers study the experience and pleasure these objects evoke, the judgments about them, and taste as an underlying sensitivity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] However, this field comes with theoretical difficulties caused by disagreements about the definitions of and relations between these concepts.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Similarly, the exact boundaries of the domain of aesthetics as a whole are disputed—it is controversial whether there is a group of essential features shared by all aesthetic phenomena or whether they are more loosely related through family resemblances.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic properties are features of an object that shape its appeal or factors that influence aesthetic evaluations.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For instance, when an art critic describes an artwork as *great*, *vivid*, or *amusing*, they express aesthetic properties of this artwork.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some aesthetic properties focus on aesthetic value in general, like *beautiful* and *ugly*; others center on more specific forms of value, such as *graceful* and *elegant*.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic properties can also refer to perceptual qualities of objects like *balanced* and *vivid*, to representational aspects like *realistic* and *distorted*, or to emotional responses such as *joyful* and *angry*.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The precise distinction between aesthetic and non-aesthetic properties is disputed.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] According to one proposal, aesthetic properties require a specific aesthetic sensitivity in addition to the sensory perception of non-aesthetic properties, going beyond simple colors, shapes, and sounds.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic properties are associated with evaluations, but not all are intrinsically good or bad.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For example, being a realistic representation may be aesthetically good in some artistic contexts and bad in others.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The school of realism argues that aesthetic properties are objective, mind-independent features of reality.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A related proposal asserts that they are emergent properties dependent on non-aesthetic properties.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] According to this view, the beauty of a painting may emerge from the right combination of colors and shapes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A different position holds that aesthetic properties are response-dependent, for example, that features of objects only qualify as aesthetic properties if they evoke aesthetic experiences in observers.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The terms "aesthetic property" and "aesthetic quality" are often used interchangeably.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some philosophers distinguish the two, associating aesthetic properties with objective features and aesthetic qualities with subjective experiences and emotional responses.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] An aesthetic object is an object with aesthetic properties.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One interpretation suggests that aesthetic objects are material entities that evoke aesthetic experiences.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] According to this view, if a person admires an oil painting, then the physical canvas and paint make up the aesthetic object.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Another interpretation, associated with the school of phenomenology, argues that aesthetic objects are not material but intentional objects.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Intentional objects are part of the content of experiences, and their existence depends on the perceiver.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] An intentional object may accurately reflect a material object, as in the case of veridical perceptions, but can also fail to do so, which happens during perceptual illusions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The phenomenological perspective focuses on the intentional object given in experience rather than the material object considered independently of the perceiver.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic values are a special type of aesthetic property.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They express the sensory appeal of an object as a qualitative measure of its aesthetic merit, encompassing both positive and negative evaluations.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic values contrast with values in other domains, such as moral, epistemic, religious, and economic values.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The aesthetic value of beauty is often singled out as a central topic of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It is a key aspect of human experience, influencing both personal decisions and cultural developments.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Often-cited examples of beautiful objects include landscapes, sunsets, humans, and artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] As a positive value, beauty contrasts with ugliness as its negative counterpart.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Beauty is typically understood as a quality of objects that involves balance or harmony and evokes admiration or pleasure when perceived, but its precise definition is debated.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some theories understand beauty as an objective feature of external objects.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Others emphasize its subjective nature, linking it to personal experience and perception.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They argue that "beauty is in the eye of the beholder" rather than in the perceived object.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Another central debate concerns the features that all beautiful objects have in common.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The so-called *classical conception of beauty* is rooted in classical antiquity and the Italian Renaissance.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Focusing on objective features, it asserts that beauty is a harmonious arrangement of parts into a coherent whole.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic hedonism, by contrast, is a subjective theory holding that a thing is beautiful if it acts as a source of aesthetic pleasure.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Other conceptions define beautiful objects in terms of intrinsic value, the manifestation of ideal forms, or as what evokes love and passion.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] In pre-modern philosophy, beauty was often treated as the only aesthetic value.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This outlook holds that beauty encompasses all that is aesthetically commendable and serves as a unifying concept of the whole domain of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] As discussions of aesthetic phenomena expanded, other aesthetic values were proposed.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For example, the sublime is another value of things that inspire feelings of awe and fear.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Further suggested values include charm, elegance, harmony, and grace.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] An aesthetic experience is an appreciation of beauty or an awareness of other aesthetic features.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] In its most typical form, it is a sensory perception of a natural object or an artwork.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It can also take other forms, such as aesthetic imagination of fictional objects described in literature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Internalist theories, like Monroe Beardsley's view, explain aesthetic experience from a first-person perspective, focusing on aspects internal to the experience, such as focus and intensity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] By contrast, externalist theories, such as George Dickie's position, argue that the key element of aesthetic experiences comes from the perceived external objects and their aesthetic properties.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Several features are associated with aesthetic experiences, but it is controversial whether any of them are essential.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic experiences usually appreciate an object for its own sake because of its sensory properties, resulting in aesthetic pleasure from a positive evaluation of the object.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This pleasure is typically said to be detached from practical concerns and can involve selfless absorption, allowing imaginative freedom or free play of mental faculties in addition to sensory perception.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some theorists associate this free play with an absence of conceptual activity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic experiences may also be normative, meaning that certain responses are appropriate, like the positive appreciation of beauty, but others are not, such as the positive appreciation of ugliness.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A central aspect of aesthetic experience is the aesthetic attitude—a special way of observing or engaging with art and nature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This attitude involves a form of pure appreciation of perceptual qualities detached from personal desires and practical concerns.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It is disinterested in this sense by engaging with an object for its own sake without ulterior motives or practical consequences.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For example, the experience of a violent storm through the aesthetic attitude may focus on its intricate patterns of lightning and thunder rather than preparing for its immediate dangers.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One characterization understands the aesthetic attitude as a natural form of apprehension that occurs on its own in certain situations.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Another outlook holds that the aesthetic attitude is a voluntary stance people can choose to adopt toward any object.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] There is debate about the extent and type of emotional engagement a disinterested stance requires, for instance, whether fear during a horror movie can be disinterested.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The aesthetic attitude is sometimes contrasted with other attitudes, such as the practical attitude, which is interested in usefulness and seeks to utilize or manipulate objects to achieve specific goals.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Similarly, it differs from the scientific attitude, which aims to explain phenomena and acquire factual knowledge about the world.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some philosophers, such as Arthur Schopenhauer and Martin Heidegger, suggest that the aesthetic attitude can reveal aspects of reality obscured in other attitudes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic experience is further associated with aesthetic pleasure—a form of enjoyment in response to natural and artistic beauty.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It is typically characterized as disinterested pleasure.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It contrasts with interested pleasure that arises from the satisfaction of desires, such as the joy of achieving a personal goal or indulging in a particular type of food one craves.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Another difference is that aesthetic pleasure does not depend on the existence of the enjoyed object, like enjoying the beauty of a sunset in a dream.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The joy in achieving a personal goal, by contrast, would be frustrated if one discovered that the achievement was merely a dream.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Philosophers like Immanuel Kant argue that aesthetic pleasure is preconceptual, meaning that it arises from a free interplay between imagination and understanding rather than from cognitive judgments or conceptual analysis.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One view distinguishes refined from unrefined aesthetic pleasures based on whether the pleasure is evoked by a cultivated taste or an immediate, instinctual response.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic pleasure is central to the characterization of many aesthetic phenomena that are said to involve or evoke such pleasure.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] However, the view that aesthetic pleasure is the defining characteristic of the entire aesthetic domain is controversial.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It faces challenges in explaining phenomena such as the sublime, drama, tragedy, and forms of modern art, which may evoke diverse emotions not primarily linked to pleasure.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic judgments are assessments of the aesthetic features and values of objects, expressed in statements like "this music is beautiful".
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They can apply both to natural objects and artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic judgments also include assessments about how or why an object has aesthetic value without explicitly determining its overall aesthetic worth, as in the statement "this music is balanced".
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Many debates in aesthetics concern the nature of aesthetic judgments, in particular, whether they can be as objective and universal as empirical judgments made by natural scientists.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Subjectivists argue that aesthetic judgments express personal feelings and dislikes without universal validity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This view is contested by objectivists, who hold that aesthetic judgments describe objective features that are independent of the particular preferences of the judging individual.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Intermediate views suggest that the standards of aesthetic judgment are grounded in stable shared dispositions rather than variable individual preferences, resulting in a form of subjective universality.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This position is reflected in Kant's view, which identifies four core features of aesthetic judgments: they are subjective, universal, disinterested, and involve an interplay of sense, imagination, and understanding.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Philosophers such as Francis Hutcheson and David Hume argue that there are general aesthetic principles or universal criteria that are applied when making aesthetic judgments.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Particularists, by contrast, assert that the unique nature of each aesthetic object requires a case-by-case evaluation that cannot be fully subsumed under general principles.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A related debate between rationalism and the immediacy thesis concerns whether aesthetic judgments are mediated through concept application and reasoning or emerge directly from sensory intuition.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic judgments rely on taste, which is a sensitivity to aesthetic qualities, a capacity to feel aesthetic pleasure, or an ability to discern beauty and other aesthetic qualities.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Taste is a type of preference expressed in immediate reactions and is sometimes understood as an inner sense or cognitive faculty.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Differences in taste are often used to explain why people disagree about aesthetic judgments and why the judgments of some people, such as art critics with extensive experience and a refined sense, carry more weight than those of casual observers.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Taste varies both among cultures and among individuals within a culture.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] There are also some cross-cultural agreements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Several philosophers argue that taste can be learned to some extent and that the judgments of experienced observers follow similar standards, suggesting the existence of social norms of right and wrong aesthetic assessments.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The term "aesthetic universal" refers to aspects of taste and other aesthetic phenomena that are shared across different cultures and societies, indicating common features of human nature underlying aesthetics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Suggested general tendencies include the dispositions to engage in artistic expressions or to derive aesthetic pleasure from appreciating these expressions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The existence of more specific shared tendencies is debated.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] An example is the idea that humans generally find savanna-like landscapes with open grassy plains and scattered trees pleasing.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Art is a central topic of aesthetics and the main subject of the philosophy of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It encompasses diverse forms, including painting, sculpture, music, dance, literature, and theater.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This field covers both artworks and the skills or activities involved in their creation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Artworks are artifacts or performances typically created by humans.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They differ in this respect from naturally occurring aesthetic objects, like landscapes and sunsets.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A central debate in the philosophy of art concerns the definition of art or how to distinguish it from non-art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] There are many theories, each offering a unique perspective on the nature of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Essentialist approaches argue that there is an essence or a set of inherent features shared by all artworks and only by them.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They often define artworks in terms of other aesthetic concepts, such as *representation*, *beauty*, or *aesthetic experience*.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] An early object-centered approach, first proposed by Plato, characterizes artworks as representations that seek to reflect or imitate certain aspects of reality.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Another definition suggests that artworks are objects designed to evoke aesthetic experiences or pleasure.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A related approach proposes that all artworks have certain aesthetic properties in common, such as beauty.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic formalism argues that specific formal features, such as a "significant form", are the hallmark of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Artist-centered approaches see artistic activity as the essential aspect of artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One conception understands artworks as special vehicles through which artists express emotions and other mental states.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Conventionalist definitions view art as a socially constructed category.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This means that it does not primarily depend on the inherent properties of objects, for example, what they represent or what forms they have.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Instead, art is defined by social and cultural agreements, which are subject to change.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A key motivation for this approach has been the emergence of modern art, which has challenged many earlier conceptions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Conventionalist definitions can explain, for instance, that even mundane ready-made objects like a urinal are considered art if conventions say so.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Institutional theories argue that the conventions are set by social institutions of the art world.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Because of this social dependence, an object considered art in one society may not be art in another society.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Historical theories, another form of conventionalism, assert that the category of art depends on established traditions and historical contexts.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They claim that an object becomes part of this category if it stands in the right relation to these traditions, for example, by being created in an artistic context and resembling other recognized artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] There are also hybrid theories that combine elements from other theories.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For instance, one approach holds that an object is an artwork if it either meets certain aesthetic standards or is conventionally regarded as art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The diversity of proposed definitions and the difficulties in reconciling them have led some philosophers to argue against the existence of precise criteria.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some conclude that a definition is strictly impossible.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Others provide vague characterizations, suggesting that the domain of art is characterized by overlapping similarities, known as family resemblance.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The ontology of art seeks to discern the fundamental categories of being to which all artworks belong.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One approach argues that artworks are universals—general or repeatable entities that can have several instances at the same time.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For example, a novel can have many copies, a film can have many screenings, and a photo can have many prints.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One version of this view distinguishes artworks as types from their instances, which are considered tokens of this type.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A different outlook rejects the idea that artworks are universals, arguing instead that they are particulars or unique concrete entities.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For them, if there are several instances, then the artwork is the collection or sum of all instances.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] According to this view, Alfred Stieglitz's photograph *The Steerage* is not a type underlying its prints but rather the collection or sum of all prints together.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A similar discussion addresses whether artworks are material objects, which exist independent of observers, or intentional objects, which exist in the experience of observers.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Pluralists argue that different types of artworks belong to distinct ontological categories.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Contextualists accept this view and further propose that the ontological category depends on the context of discussion.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Deflationism is skeptical about the fundamental existence of artworks in any form.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It acknowledges that the term *art* may be practically useful in everyday language but rejects that it refers to any fundamental entities of reality.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some distinctions focus on the medium used to express artistic ideas.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For example, paintings typically use paint, such as oil or acrylic paint, which is distributed on a surface, whereas dance involves bodily movements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Similarly, music is performed using instruments and voice to produce sounds, and literature relies on language.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Hybrid forms like opera and film combine several of these elements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Another distinction is between performance works and object works.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Performance works, like a song performed on stage, are dynamically enacted in time, whereas object works, like a painting, have a more static nature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Artworks can also be classified by art historic style, such as impressionism and surrealism, and by their intended purpose, like political and religious art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The meaning of an artwork is what is involved in understanding it or comprehending what it communicates, encompassing factors such as representation and expression.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Certain aspects of meaning may be directly accessible; others require in-depth interpretation, for example, to grasp symbolic or metaphorical elements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Understanding influences aesthetic experience, and for certain artworks, a comprehensive understanding may be required to fully appreciate them.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One approach to the analysis of meaning is the distinction between form and content.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Content refers to what is presented, such as the depicted topic, expressed ideas, and conceptual messages.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Form refers to how the content is presented, such as medium, technique, composition, and style.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Form encompasses modes of presentation in different art forms, like color and spatial arrangement in painting, harmony and rhythm in music, and narrative voice and plot structure in literature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Representation is a depiction of real or imagined entities.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For example, a portrait painting represents a person, and a fantasy novel represents an imaginary chain of events.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Similarity is a crucial element in many forms of artistic representation, meaning that the artwork resembles the depicted entity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Representation can also happen through other means, such as conventional symbols and established codes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It is particularly prevalent in certain art forms and styles, such as classical art and realism.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Since antiquity, representation has been a key concept in theories of art, such as Plato's idea of defining art as imitation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] However, it is controversial whether representation plays a central role in all art forms, including music and abstract modern art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Expression is the conveyance of psychological states, such as emotions, moods, and attitudes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For example, a painter may depict a barren landscape in muted colors to express sadness, and a musician might use a fast tempo and upbeat melody to convey excitement.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The expressed mental states often align with the artist's personal experience.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] However, this is not necessarily the case, and artists may explore psychological states they observed in others or entirely fictional experiences.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] An artwork can express a mental state like sadness by evoking it in the experience of the audience.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Alternatively, the expression can also happen if observers recognize the presence of sadness in the artwork even if they do not personally feel it.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Expression theories consider expression a core feature of artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They characterize artworks as expressions of the artist's mind, focusing on creativity and originality in the manifestation of aesthetic experiences.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The process of interpretation is the attempt to uncover the meaning of an artwork to understand its significance and value.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] In the widest sense, interpretation encompasses any way of assigning meaning, including obvious descriptions of depicted entities and explanations of literal word meanings.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Interpretations aim to discover underlying aspects that are relevant to the understanding and appreciation of the artwork.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The terms *interpretation* and *criticism* are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] However, criticism is typically associated with more components, like a general description of the criticized artwork and a classification of style and genre.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Criticism also explains the art-historical background and evaluates positive and negative qualities.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Critics sometimes propose conflicting interpretations of the same artwork.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] According to critical monism, there is only one comprehensive correct interpretation, implying that conflicting interpretations cannot both be correct.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Critical pluralism, by contrast, asserts that there can be different but equally valid interpretations and that it is not always possible to determine which of two conflicting interpretations is superior.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A similar debate addresses whether interpretations can be true or false in an objective sense.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Several frameworks of interpretation have been proposed.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] According to intentionalism, the meaning of an artwork is determined by the author's intent—their reasons and motives that led to the creation of the artwork.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This typically involves analyzing the ideas the artist aimed to express but can also include a biographical analysis to learn about psychological and social circumstances in the artist's life.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Intentionalism is a controversial theory, termed the *intentional fallacy* by its critics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Some objections point to cases where the author's intention cannot be known, where the author cannot be identified, or where no traditional author exists, as in artworks created by artificial intelligence.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] In these cases, meaning would be inaccessible or non-existent.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Other objections assert that an artist may fail to accurately express their intention or may manifest unintended aesthetic features, suggesting that an artwork can contain both less and more than the artist intended.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] An alternative to intentionalism argues that meaning is determined by artistic, stylistic, linguistic, and other cultural conventions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For example, linguistic conventions determine the literal meanings of words and thereby influence the overall meaning of a poem.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Another framework holds that meaning is shaped by how the audience, rather than the author, interprets or would interpret the intention underlying the work.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Artistic formalism proposes a different approach by focusing interpretation exclusively on formal or perceptual features of artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aestheticism and instrumentalism are theories about the value of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Aestheticism asserts that the primary value of art lies in its intrinsic aesthetic merits, independent of any external purposes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This idea of the autonomy of art is expressed in the slogan "art for art's sake".
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Strong forms of aestheticism not only disregard external purposes but see them as detrimental influences that undermine artistic integrity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Instrumentalism, by contrast, explains the value of art by the effects it has on other domains.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It understands art as a means to things such as moral education, spiritual growth, therapeutic benefits, and social cohesion.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The individual arts are practices or disciplines in the domain of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They encompass a wide range of fields, including traditionally established forms such as painting, music, and literature, as well as newer types like video games.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] One classification divides them into visual arts, literary arts, and performance arts.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The boundaries between these categories are not always clear, and alternative classifications have been proposed.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Painting is a visual art in which a painter applies colors to a surface.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It allows for a diverse range of motives and styles, and is often considered a paradigm form of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The representation of real entities plays a central role in many forms of painting, ranging from landscapes and people to historic events.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This process involves artistic choices that go beyond simple replication, such as guiding the viewer's attention to specific aspects or highlighting important but easily overlooked features.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The issue of representation is also crucial in photography, a visual art shaped by technological developments in camera design and editing processes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A key topic in the philosophy of photography concerns its mechanical manner of authentically representing real objects, frequently drawing parallels and distinctions with painting.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The status of photographs as true artworks is disputed, with critics arguing that the mechanical nature of capturing images lacks the necessary artistic creativity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Music is a performance art in which sounds are combined to create aesthetic patterns, relying on aspects such as melody and rhythm.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Unlike painting and photography, it is typically less associated with objective representation and more closely linked to the expression of emotions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] A key discussion in the philosophy of music concerns the definition of music or the criteria under which a combination of sounds qualifies as music.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Proposals range from objective criteria, such as the patterns of how sounds are organized, to subjective criteria, focusing on audience experience and interpretation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Dance is another performance art in which dancers create aesthetic patterns through a series of bodily movements, often following a choreography.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It is typically accompanied by music and shares with music an emphasis on expressive features.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Architecture is the art or craft of designing and building, encompassing a wide range of structures from monuments and cathedrals to skyscrapers and residential homes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It typically combines aesthetic with functional goals, seeking to create buildings that are both visually appealing and practically useful.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] This dual nature is a central topic of the philosophy of architecture, with one theory suggesting that mere buildings can be distinguished from artistic architecture by the presence of decorative elements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Sculpture is another art form that, like architecture, involves the creation of three-dimensional works.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Sculptures are usually static objects made of robust materials like stone, metal, and wood, but may also include dynamic elements, as is the case for kinetic sculptures.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Key discussions in the philosophy of sculpture address the definition, representational aspects, and aesthetic features of sculptures as well as the influence of the chosen material.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Literature has language as its primary medium.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] In its widest sense, literature encompasses any written document.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] However, the term is typically used in a narrower sense in aesthetics for forms of writing that belong to the high arts, such as poems, novels, and drama.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Literature as an art is often characterized by its deliberate, elaborate, and organized use of language, but there is no universally accepted demarcation between artistic literature and other forms of writing.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Poetry is a distinct form of literature often written in verses composed of several lines that may follow specific patterns, such as meter and rhyme.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Many poems are characterized by an economical use of language that seeks to evoke specific experiences while being difficult to paraphrase.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Theater is a performance art that combines elements from other art forms.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] It typically includes a carefully prepared set or stage where actors perform, usually incorporating storytelling and sound design to create immersive experiences.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Theater is performed before a live audience, which can create a sense of immediacy that is less prevalent in related art forms, such as film.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Film also integrates aspects from several artistic disciplines but relies more heavily on technological means of recording and editing.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Films can involve actors but may also include animated characters or document real-life events.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They are normally the result of collaborative efforts of many people, which complicates the identification of a singular author in the traditional sense.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Video games are a more recent form of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Like theater and film, they usually blend visual, auditory, and narrative elements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] They typically stand out through their emphasis on player interaction, allowing active exploration of and engagement with the game world.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] The status of films and video games as serious forms of art is disputed.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] Proponents tend to emphasize their aesthetic qualities; critics often point to their association with mass production and popular culture as counterarguments.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p01] For video games, a related debate centers on the elements of competition and winning, questioning whether these elements run counter to the spirit of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Aesthetic phenomena are investigated in several fields.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Some areas examine the relationship between aesthetics and other branches of philosophy or compare different artistic traditions; others study aesthetic elements in everyday life or engage in scientific inquiry using empirical methods.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Ethics is the branch of philosophy that studies moral phenomena in general and right behavior in particular.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Artworks can have ethical consequences by influencing how people feel, perceive, and evaluate their circumstances.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For example, artworks can glorify violence and reinforce biases, just as they can inspire empathy and challenge societal norms.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] As a result, art is also relevant to the field of politics since it can steer political sentiment to legitimize authority or mobilize resistance, thereby influencing voter attitudes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Artworks can also explore morally relevant topics without expressing a clear positive or negative evaluation, such as a novel examining an ethical dilemma without favoring one solution over the others.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Since both ethics and aesthetics deal with values, philosophers seek to clarify the relationship between moral and aesthetic values, proposing several theories of their interaction.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Ethicism asserts that the moral value of an artwork can increase its aesthetic value, while ethical defects may undermine its artistic merit.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This view is reversed by immoralism, which suggests that in some cases, moral flaws enhance aesthetic experience.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Autonomism rejects both positions, arguing that these domains of evaluation are independent.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Scientific approaches rooted in psychology and related fields employ empirical methods to conduct inquiries and justify hypotheses.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The psychology of aesthetics examines the mental processes involved in the perception and appreciation of beauty and art, using methods such as experimentation, observation, and surveys.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Experimental aesthetics is an early and influential approach pioneered by Gustav Fechner.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It follows a bottom-up methodology that starts with human sensation, investigating preferences to simple physical stimuli, such as basic colors and shapes.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Gestalt psychology relies on a more holistic outlook, examining how composition and object placement influence aesthetic experience, like the relationship between balanced organization and a sense of calm.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Some works, such as Daniel Berlyne's approach, shift the focus from perception to emotion, suggesting that features like novelty and complexity cause arousal and that the right amount of arousal is pleasurable.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Psychological analysis also examines the temporal structure of aesthetic experiences of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] One outlook identifies two phases: an initial impression in which the observer forms a rough general idea of the artwork's topic, structure, and meaning, followed by a focal analysis of more specific features.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Research further explores how circumstances influence aesthetic experience, like the contrast between encountering a painting in a museum or a shopping mall.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Along with physical circumstances, social and personal factors also influence aesthetic experience, such as group dynamics, prior knowledge, and the motivation for seeking the experience.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Evolutionary psychology analyzes mental phenomena as products of natural selection.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It asserts that genetic variations responsible for new capacities are passed on to future generations if they enhance survival and reproduction.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Adopting this approach, evolutionary aesthetics interprets beauty and other aesthetic experiences as adaptive traits that guide fitness-relevant preferences.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Examples are aesthetic preferences for environments conducive to survival, such as landscapes resembling the African savanna, and sexual selection by identifying genetically fit mates.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] By focusing on the relatively permanent biological nature of humans, evolutionary psychology sees aesthetic values as universal or transcultural patterns of taste and appreciation, contrasting with subjectivist theories that understand aesthetic values as cultural constructs.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Neuroaesthetics applies neuroscientific insights and methods to study the relationship between brain activity and aesthetic experience.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Aesthetic experiences arise from brain processes responsible for organizing sensory stimuli, forming cognitive interpretations, and generating emotional responses.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Neuroaesthetics examines these processes using empirical methods, including neuroimaging techniques like fMRI.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In one type of experiment, participants view artworks, some considered beautiful and others ugly, with researchers noting that the brain area known as the orbitofrontal cortex is more active when viewing beautiful paintings.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Cognitive science, another field, employs an interdisciplinary approach to study mental phenomena by examining how they access and transform information.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] An influential theory, suggested by Ernst Gombrich, analyzes aesthetic experience through the interplay of low-level and high-level information processes: sensory processes provide low-level information, which is organized and interpreted using high-level conceptual background knowledge.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Another approach analyzes aesthetic representation through the modularity of mind—the hypothesis that the mind is composed of mental modules that function independently.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It argues that paintings represent real objects by triggering the same mental modules responsible for the recognition of those objects.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Comparative aesthetics examines diverse aesthetic traditions, analyzing the similarities and differences in their standards of beauty and theoretical approaches.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For example, the focus in Western aesthetics on high art and its separation from everyday affairs is not common in most other traditions, for which art is typically closely integrated with practical functions in everyday life, including religion and moral education.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Artistic differences between different traditions also encompass dominant media, common styles, and chosen motifs.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The comparison of cultural products from different traditions presents conceptual challenges associated with tradition-specific aesthetic concepts and standards of evaluation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The uncritical application of standards from one tradition to evaluate the works of another can result in cultural imperialism.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] At the same time, these differences provide opportunities to artists and philosophers to incorporate new elements and explore novel perspectives.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Indian aesthetics draws a close connection between artistic activity and religious practice.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It argues that artistic expression is a spiritual endeavor that should be informed by knowledge of the self and reality, express devotion to the divine, and avoid attachments to the fruits of the activity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Traditional Indian aesthetics analyzes art in terms of basic life emotions, called rasas, such as delight, humor, sadness, and anger.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It sees art as a play that imitates reality by conveying experiences of the rasas.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Its focus is on the universal expressions of human emotional life rather than person-specific feelings.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This school of thought identifies artistic creativity as the ability to harness the full potential of the medium, like colors, sounds, and words, to convey experiential universals.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For the audience, it recommends an aesthetic attitude characterized by a psychic distance from private concerns to transcend the personal self and become receptive to universal elements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Chinese aesthetics emphasizes the spontaneous nature of artistic creativity and its connection to the moral and spiritual domains.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It argues that art should foster harmony within society and align with the natural order of the universe.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In this role, art is both self-expression and self-cultivation aimed at promoting social well-being.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The main focus of Chinese aesthetics is on poetry, painting, and calligraphy, known as the three perfections.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This tradition influenced Japanese aesthetics, which is characterized by its interest in nature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Different art styles in this tradition are shaped by religious outlooks, particularly Shinto and Buddhism.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Japanese theories of art stress the interrelation between the experience of the artist and the response of the audience.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Islamic philosophers see art as a means of communicating philosophical and religious truths, making them accessible to the general public without requiring abstract theoretical thought.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Thinkers such as Al-Farabi and Avicenna argued that imagination rather than reasoning underlies artistic creation and appreciation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] According to this view, art imitates reality and evokes emotions to convey underlying truths and positively influence behavior.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Religious teachings play a central role in Islamic aesthetics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For example, the belief that Allah is transcendent and boundless has resulted in the avoidance of figurative depictions and the emphasis on abstract art forms.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] African aesthetics emphasizes the intuitive and emotional nature of art, highlighting its communal function in social life.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Early scholarship on this tradition was typically conducted from an ethnocentric perspective using Western aesthetic standards to interpret and evaluate African art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This usually resulted in the portrayal of African artworks as exotic curiosities that lack the sophistication of high art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The emergence of indigenous scholarship in the 20th century sought to correct this interpretation, arguing that the emphasis on moral, emotional, and intuitive aspects reflects different artistic standards rather than a deficiency.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This school of thought, often associated with the concept of Négritude, focuses on the importance of feelings in contrast to abstraction and intellectual analysis.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Environmental aesthetics deals with the appreciation of nature, including elements such as forests, mountain ranges, rivers, and flowers.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It encompasses both transient appearances, such as the fleeting beauty of a landscape during sunset, and enduring aspects, such as the majesty of a centuries-old tree.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This field focuses on sensory and formal qualities associated with beauty and related aesthetic qualities.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In this respect, it contrasts with the philosophy of art, which typically emphasizes the interpretation of underlying meanings associated with expression and representation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Some approaches to environmental aesthetics also consider the impact of background knowledge on the aesthetic experience of nature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For instance, ecological awareness of the intricate relationships within an ecosystem can shape the appreciation of a woodland environment by understanding it as a habitat of diverse species.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In its broadest sense, environmental aesthetics encompasses the appreciation of any environment, including those created by humans.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This inquiry is closely associated with everyday aesthetics, which examines aesthetic phenomena encountered in daily life.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Everyday aesthetics covers both public and private environments, ranging from modern cities and industrial sites to private homes and backyards, as well as personal adornments and consumer products, such as clothing, hairstyles, industrial design, and web design.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The aesthetics of popular art, a related discipline, investigates aesthetic qualities in popular culture and compares the evaluative standards of popular art with those of high or fine art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For example, it studies the contrast between commercial mass art and experimental avant-garde and explores specific types of popular art, such as kitsch.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Art plays a central role in the field of religion and manifests in many forms, including paintings, sculptures, architecture, music, dance, and literature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Its key characteristic comes from its religious function, such as conveying theological and moral teachings, representing symbolic truths, inspiring religious experiences, and aiding devotional practices.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Religious art is part of all major religions and was the dominant art form during ancient and medieval times.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Its influence began to wane in the modern period due to secularization.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This shift is also reflected in developments in the philosophy of art that introduced a focus on disinterestedness and the autonomy of aesthetic experience from external purposes, including religious goals.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Several theories of aesthetics are associated with specific philosophical schools of thought.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Marxist aesthetics examines the relationship between art, class structure, and social ideology, exploring how art can enforce or challenge established power hierarchies.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Feminist aesthetics criticizes male biases in aesthetic theory and artistic practice while discussing alternatives.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It investigates unfair social institutions and aesthetic standards that disadvantage women and exclude them from the art world.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] An example is the male gaze—a cultural phenomenon that treats women as objects of male spectatorship rather than as artistic creators.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Postmodern aesthetics is a diverse movement that challenges established concepts and theories in the field of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It typically rejects the focus on disinterested pleasure, the autonomy of art from other domains, and the distinction between high and popular art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It tends to promote a pluralism that embraces diversity, playfulness, and irony.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The term mathematical beauty refers to aesthetic qualities of abstract mathematical concepts and theories.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For instance, a mathematical proof may be considered beautiful if it demonstrates a profound insight in an effective manner or reveals an underlying unity of seemingly disparate mathematical ideas.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The aesthetics of science examines aesthetic judgments about scientific theories and practices, including the role of beauty and creativity in the construction of models.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Computer art involves the use of computers in the creation of artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It can take many forms, ranging from minor digital enhancements of existing artworks to entirely new creations generated using complex algorithms.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Its abstract nature, based on symbolic representation and manipulation of electronic signals, distinguishes computer art from traditional forms of art, which rely on more tangible media.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This medium offers new artistic possibilities, such as virtual reality and interactivity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Rapid developments in artificial intelligence in the 21st century have significantly impacted computer art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] They include the emergence of generative models—systems that are trained using existing media to create new texts, images, music, or videos in response to verbal descriptions of the intended result.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Examples include ChatGPT, Stable Diffusion, MuseNet, and RunwayML.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Meta-aesthetics examines the fundamental assumptions and concepts underlying aesthetics.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It asks about the existence of aesthetic facts, the meaning of aesthetic statements, and the ways of acquiring aesthetic knowledge.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] A central meta-aesthetic debate between realism and anti-realism addresses whether there are mind-independent aesthetic facts.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] A related discussion between cognitivism and non-cognitivism considers whether aesthetic statements can be objectively true or primarily express personal emotions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Aesthetics has its roots in ancient thought, which typically interpreted beauty as a metaphysical phenomenon associated with the order of the cosmos.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In ancient Greek philosophy, early explorations of the nature of beauty are found in Pythagorean philosophy in the 5th and 4th centuries BCE.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This tradition proposed that beauty arises from the proportion and harmony between different elements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In works like the *Philebus* and *Symposium*, Plato (427–347 BCE) analyzed pure beauty as an immutable form that exists independently of matter.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] He argued that material entities are beautiful if they participate in the form of beauty.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Plato understood art as a craft that seeks to imitate and represent material entities.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] He acknowledged that art has some didactic value but was overall critical of it, asserting that its derivative nature, based on imitation of sensible features, cannot lead to true knowledge.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) examined aesthetics through the lens of poetry, providing a detailed analysis in his book *Poetics*.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] He agreed with Plato's idea that art is a form of imitation but adopted a more positive outlook, proposing that it can reveal universal truths.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Aristotle suggested that successful artistic imitation is pleasurable and can have therapeutic or cathartic effects.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] By linking this pleasure to beauty, he tried to explain why the imitation of unpleasurable phenomena, like tragic stories, can be enjoyable.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Also influenced by Plato, Plotinus (204–270 CE) argued that beauty is not based on sensory symmetries or simple proportions but embodies an underlying order, harmony, and unity associated with the ultimate source of creation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In ancient India, the Natya Shastra, traditionally attributed to Bharata (c.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] 200 CE), formulated the rasa theory of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This theory posits that the goal of art is to convey fundamental life emotions as experiential universals of human existence.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In ancient China, the philosophy of art was shaped by Confucianism.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It emphasized self-cultivation and the relation between nature and human culture.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] During the medieval period, the rise of Christianity led Western aesthetic thinkers to blend ancient Greek thought with religious teachings, often in the form of philosophical theology.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Influenced by Plato and Plotinus, Augustine of Hippo (354–430 CE) explored the distinction between artistic creation, which transforms matter, and divine creation, which brings forth existence out of nothing.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] He thought that all beauty originates from God and analyzed it in terms of unity, equality, number, proportion, and order.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Thomas Aquinas defined beauty as what brings pleasure upon perception.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For him, the mind plays a central role in this process since beauty lies in the immaterial form of the perceived object that the mind recognizes in the sensory data.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Aquinas saw beauty as a basic category of being and identified it with proportion, radiance, and integrity.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] An integration of Greek philosophy and religious thought also happened in the Islamic world.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] 950 CE) associated beauty with pleasure and understood it as a degree of perfection and a divine attribute of Allah.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] 980 – 1037 CE) distinguished sensible from intelligible beauty and explored psychological processes underlying aesthetic judgments, such as the role of imagination.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Meanwhile, in India, the rasa theory of art expanded to also encompass devotional practices, including efforts to portray or evoke profound religious experiences of the union with the divine.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] 1025 CE) elaborated the spiritual dimension of the rasa theory, drawing a sharp distinction between ordinary worldly emotions and rasas as transcendent aesthetic emotions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] 5th to 6th centuries CE) combined Daoist and Confucian ideas, suggesting that artists align with the natural order of the universe and spontaneously express the movement of life in their artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] He also proposed a set of basic principles of painting.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] 1090 CE) argued that artworks reflect the moral character and spiritual outlook of the artist, which he saw as a central factor of the artwork's aesthetic value.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] During this period, the growing influence of Buddhism on Chinese aesthetic thought led to an artistic shift from objective reality to subjective experiences as a result of Buddhist teachings on the illusory nature of reality.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The medieval period in the West came to an end with the emergence of the Renaissance starting in the 15th century.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This change led to the revival of classical aesthetic ideals while secularization paved the way for rationalist inquiries into general laws of beauty and empiricist analyses of sensory and emotional experiences in the subsequent Age of Enlightenment.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Modern aesthetics emerged in the 18th century, as philosophers engaged more systematically with the subject.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] A key step in this process happened through the philosophy of Alexander Baumgarten (1714–1762), who first conceived aesthetics as a distinct field of inquiry: the science of sensory cognitions or the study of what is sensed and imagined.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In British philosophy, Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) followed ideas of the third Earl of Shaftesbury (1671–1713) and provided an early theory of taste, conceptualizing it as an internal sense responsible for aesthetic apprehension.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This outlook inspired David Hume (1711–1776) to develop a subjective theory of beauty, understanding it as a pleasurable sentiment caused by perceptions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] He combined this perspective with the idea that beauty follows intersubjective standards as shared principles of taste governing which objects are experienced as beautiful.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Immanuel Kant (1724–1804) expanded Hume's idea that aesthetic judgments are both subjective and universal, arguing that the underlying pleasure must be disinterested to follow universal standards.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] According to Kant, this type of pleasure comes from a free play in which the mental faculties of imagination and understanding harmoniously interact.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In response to earlier theories by Edmund Burke (1729–1797), Kant also examined the sublime as a distinct aesthetic quality.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Kant's thought inspired diverse developments in German philosophy.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Friedrich Schiller (1759–1805) saw art as a unifying phenomenon that synthesizes different basic human drives in a type of play.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] J. von Schelling (1775–1854) shared a similar perspective, arguing that art reconciles opposites and reveals the underlying unity of the self and nature.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Hegel (1770–1831) studied aesthetics through his philosophical system of absolute idealism, seeing artistic beauty as the sensory manifestation of truth.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Combining Kantian and Indian philosophy, Arthur Schopenhauer (1788–1860) understood disinterested aesthetic experience as a suspension of the will, resulting in a temporary peace of mind by interrupting the cycle of striving and suffering.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] He inspired the Chinese philosopher Wang Guowei (1877–1927), who integrated Schopenhauer's ideas with Buddhist thought.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Wang viewed the goal of art as the creation of worlds within the world, which are open to disinterested reflection.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Friedrich Nietzsche (1844–1900) rejected the disinterestedness of aesthetic experience and the autonomy of art from other domains.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Instead, he considered art an expression of the struggle between opposing life forces, seeing it as a vehicle of transformation and life affirmation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Following the thought of Karl Marx (1818–1883), Marxist aesthetic philosophers like Leon Trotsky (1879–1940) and Georg Lukács (1885–1971) examined how art reflects and shapes social ideologies and power hierarchies.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Drawing from Marxist ideas, Theodor Adorno (1903–1969) critiqued the commodification of art and explored its ability to express alienation and challenge societal norms.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Also adopting a Marxist perspective, Walter Benjamin (1892–1940) studied how advances in technological reproducibility transform art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Romanticist thought emphasized artistic originality, creativity, and the expression of profound feelings, as formulated in the works of J.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It saw artworks as products of human genius that defy rule-based understanding.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This school of thought inspired the theory of expressionism, which asserts that the primary function of art is to communicate emotions and other mental states.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It was examined by thinkers such as Leo Tolstoy (1828–1910), Benedetto Croce (1866–1952), and R.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Intentionalism, a closely related position, focuses on the author's intent as the source of meaning of artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Monroe Beardsley (1915–1985) opposed this view, arguing that meaning is not fixed by private intentions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Sigmund Freud (1856–1939) and Carl Jung (1875–1961) interpreted art through a psychoanalytic perspective as expressions of the unconscious, an approach also later explored by Richard Wollheim (1923–2005).
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, aestheticism became a prominent view in English-speaking philosophy.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For example, Walter Pater (1839–1894) and Oscar Wilde (1854–1900) proposed that art is an end in itself without an ulterior purpose.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Pragmatists rejected this outlook and the idea that aesthetic experience is disinterested.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For instance, John Dewey (1859–1952) proposed in his 1934 book *Art as Experience* that the value of art lies in the unique experiences it provides, which can lead to individual and societal improvements.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Formalism became another influential theory of art in the early 20th century.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] It dismisses the focus on expressive and representational aspects and argues instead that artworks are defined by formal features, like the arrangement of perceptual qualities.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Clive Bell (1881–1964), a major proponent of this view, termed this arrangement "significant form".
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The emergence of Dadaism and conceptual art challenged traditional definitions of art based on intrinsic features of artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Danto (1924–2013) and George Dickie (1926–2020) to propose institutional definitions, arguing that social conventions set by the art world determine which objects are artworks.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Mary Mothersill (1923–2008) challenged these developments.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] She aimed to restore earlier conceptions of beauty associated with Aquinas, Hume, and Kant, focusing on the apprehension of aesthetic qualities.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] In continental philosophy, the school of phenomenology studied the immediate experience of art.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For example, it examined how artworks can depict unreal objects, how imagination is involved in the process, and how art can reveal features of reality.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] This tradition is closely related to existentialist aesthetics, which views artworks as expressions of human freedom that can authentically portray central aspects of the human condition.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] The philosophy of Martin Heidegger (1889–1976) influenced both traditions.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] He criticized the focus on disinterested pleasure found in modern philosophy of art, arguing that artworks can reveal truths about human existence and provide new perspectives of understanding.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Heidegger's student Hans-Georg Gadamer (1900–2002) further investigated the relation between art and truth, examining aesthetic experience and traditional theories through phenomenological analysis and hermeneutic interpretation.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Postmodern thinkers, like Roland Barthes (1915–1980) and Jacques Derrida (1930–2004), challenged the separation of art from everyday life and the idea that artworks have a stable meaning or universal value.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] They suggested instead that artistic merit depends on historical and cultural contexts.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] Starting in the 1970s, feminist perspectives challenged male-centric theories and practices within aesthetic philosophy and the art world.
[src:aesthetic/aesthetic-p02] For example, Simone de Beauvoir (1908–1986) and Luce Irigaray (born 1930) explored how feminine perspectives are marginalized by masculine standards.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:aesthetic/common-noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] A **noun phrase** – or **NP** or **nominal (phrase)** – is a phrase that usually has a noun or pronoun as its head, and has the same grammatical functions as a noun.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Noun phrases are very common cross-linguistically, and they may be the most frequently occurring phrase type.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Noun phrases often function as verb subjects and objects, as predicative expressions, and as complements of prepositions.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] One NP can be embedded inside another NP; for instance, *some of his constituents* has as a constituent the shorter NP *his constituents*.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] In some theories of grammar, noun phrases with determiners are analyzed as having the determiner as the head of the phrase, see for instance Chomsky (1995) and Hudson (1990).
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Some examples of noun phrases are underlined in the sentences below.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Noun phrases can be identified by the possibility of pronoun substitution, as is illustrated in the examples below.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] A string of words that can be replaced by a single pronoun without rendering the sentence grammatically unacceptable is a noun phrase.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] As to whether the string must contain at least two words, see the following section.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Traditionally, a phrase is understood to contain two or more words.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The traditional progression in the size of syntactic units is *word < phrase < clause*, and in this approach a single word (such as a noun or pronoun) would not be referred to as a phrase.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] However, many modern schools of syntax – especially those that have been influenced by X-bar theory – make no such restriction.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Here many single words are judged to be phrases based on a desire for theory-internal consistency.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] A phrase is deemed to be a word or a combination of words that appears in a set syntactic position, for instance in subject position or object position.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The words in bold are called phrases since they appear in the syntactic positions where multiple-word phrases (i.e. traditional phrases) can appear.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] This practice takes the constellation to be primitive rather than the words themselves.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The word *he*, for instance, functions as a pronoun, but within the sentence it also functions as a noun phrase.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The phrase structure grammars of the Chomskyan tradition (government and binding theory and the minimalist program) are primary examples of theories that apply this understanding of phrases.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Other grammars such as dependency grammars are likely to reject this approach to phrases, since they take the words themselves to be primitive.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] For them, phrases must contain two or more words.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] A typical noun phrase consists of a noun (the head of the phrase) together with zero or more dependents of various types.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The allowability, form and position of these elements depend on the syntax of the language in question.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] In English, determiners, adjectives (and some adjective phrases) and noun modifiers precede the head noun, whereas the heavier units – phrases and clauses – generally follow it.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] This is part of a strong tendency in English to place heavier constituents to the right, making English more of a head-initial language.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Japanese and Turkish) are more likely to place all modifiers before the head noun.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Other languages, such as French, often place even single-word adjectives after the noun.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Noun phrases can take different forms than that described above, for example when the head is a pronoun rather than a noun, or when elements are linked with a coordinating conjunction such as *and*, *or*, *but*.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] For more information about the structure of noun phrases in English, see English grammar § Phrases.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Noun phrases typically bear argument functions.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] That is, the syntactic functions that they fulfill are those of the arguments of the main clause predicate, particularly those of subject, object and predicative expression.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] They also function as arguments in such constructs as participial phrases and prepositional phrases.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Sometimes a noun phrase can also function as an adjunct of the main clause predicate, thus taking on an adverbial function, e.g.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The situation is complicated by the fact that in some contexts a noun phrase may nonetheless be used without a determiner (as in *I like big houses*); in this case the phrase may be described as having a "null determiner".
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] In the original X-bar theory, the two respective types of entity are called noun phrase (NP) and N-bar (N, N′).
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Thus in the sentence *Here is the big house*, both *house* and *big house* are N-bars, while *the big house* is a noun phrase.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] In the sentence *I like big houses*, both *houses* and *big houses* are N-bars, but *big houses* also functions as a noun phrase (in this case without an explicit determiner).
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] In some modern theories of syntax, however, what are called "noun phrases" above are no longer considered to be headed by a noun, but by the determiner (which may be null), and they are thus called *determiner phrases* (DP) instead of noun phrases.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] This analysis of noun phrases is widely referred to as the *DP hypothesis*.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] It has been the preferred analysis of noun phrases in the minimalist program from its start (since the early 1990s), though the arguments in its favor tend to be theory-internal.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] By taking the determiner, a function word, to be head over the noun, a structure is established that is analogous to the structure of the finite clause, with a complementizer.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Apart from the minimalist program, however, the DP hypothesis is rejected by most other modern theories of syntax and grammar, in part because these theories lack the relevant functional categories.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Dependency grammars, for instance, almost all assume the traditional NP analysis of noun phrases.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] For illustrations of different analyses of noun phrases depending on whether the DP hypothesis is rejected or accepted, see the next section.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The representation of noun phrases using parse trees depends on the basic approach to syntactic structure adopted.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The layered trees of many phrase structure grammars grant noun phrases an intricate structure that acknowledges a hierarchy of functional projections.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Dependency grammars, in contrast, since the basic architecture of dependency places a major limitation on the amount of structure that the theory can assume, produce simple, relatively flat structures for noun phrases.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The representation also depends on whether the noun or the determiner is taken to be the head of the phrase (see the discussion of the DP hypothesis in the previous section).
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] Below are some possible trees for the two noun phrases *the big house* and *big houses* (as in the sentences *Here is the big house* and *I like big houses*).
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The following trees represent a more complex phrase.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] For simplicity, only dependency-based trees are given.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The first tree is based on the traditional assumption that nouns, rather than determiners, are the heads of phrases.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The head noun *picture* has the four dependents *the*, *old*, *of Fred*, and *that I found in the drawer*.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The tree shows how the lighter dependents appear as pre-dependents (preceding their head) and the heavier ones as post-dependents (following their head).
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The second tree assumes the DP hypothesis, namely that determiners serve as phrase heads, rather than nouns.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] The determiner *the* is now depicted as the head of the entire phrase, thus making the phrase a determiner phrase.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] There is still a noun phrase present (*old picture of Fred that I found in the drawer*) but this phrase is below the determiner.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] An early conception of the noun phrase can be found in *First work in English* by Alexander Murison.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] In this conception a noun phrase is "the infinitive of the verb" (p.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] 146), which may appear "in any position in the sentence where a noun may appear".
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] For example, *to be just is more important than to be generous* has two underlined infinitives which may be replaced by nouns, as in *justice is more important than generosity*.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] This same conception can be found in subsequent grammars, such as 1878's *A Tamil Grammar* or 1882's *Murby's English grammar and analysis*, where the conception of an X phrase is a phrase that can stand in for X.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] By 1912, the concept of a noun phrase as being based around a noun can be found, for example, "an adverbial noun phrases is a group of words of which the noun is the base word, that tells the time or place of an action, or how long, how far, or how much".
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] By 1924, the idea of a noun phrase being a noun plus dependents seems to be established.
[src:aesthetic/noun-phrase] For example, "Note order of words in noun-phrase--noun + adj. + genitive" suggests a more modern conception of noun phrases.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] While all scissors largely follow the same working principle, heavy-duty scissors intended for cutting tough materials tend to be called shears instead of scissors (e.g. pruning shears and grass shears), and some larger, two-handed implements are called *trimmers* instead (e.g. hedge trimmer).
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Choosing the optimal type of scissors/shears is crucial, as otherwise it can cause unwanted damage to the target material and/or the instrument itself.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Surgical scissors, used to divide tissues and trim/reshape implants during surgical operations, have even a greater variety to deal with different anatomical and procedural circumstances.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Most scissors have a ringed handle to allow readily opening for repeated cutting, and some even have spring between the shanks to assist opening (especially for shears with straight handle).
[src:aesthetic/scissor] While historically inexpensive, mass-produced scissors often have bare metal handles, modern scissors are often designed ergonomically with composite thermoplastic and rubber covering on handles, which are more comfortable for the hand.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The noun *scissors* is treated as a plural noun and therefore takes a plural verb (e.g., *these scissors are*).
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Alternatively, the tool is referred to by the singular phrase *a pair of scissors*.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The word *shears* is used to describe similar instruments that are larger in size and for heavier cutting.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company in Hangzhou, China, has been manufacturing scissors since 1663.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Pivoted scissors were not manufactured in large numbers until 1761, when Robert Hinchliffe of Sheffield produced the first pair of modern-day scissors made of hardened and polished cast steel.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] His major challenge was to form the bows; first, he made them solid, then drilled a hole, and then filed away metal to make this large enough to admit the user's fingers.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] This process was laborious, and apparently Hinchliffe improved upon it in order to increase production.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Hinchliffe lived in Cheney Square (now the site of Sheffield Town Hall), and set up a sign identifying himself as a "fine scissor manufacturer".
[src:aesthetic/scissor] He achieved strong sales in London and elsewhere.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The vast majority of global scissor manufacturing takes place in China.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] As of 2019, China was responsible for 64.3% of worldwide scissors exports.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] When combined with Chinese Taipei exports, this rises to 68.3%.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company, founded in 1663, is one of the oldest continuously operating scissor manufacturers in the world.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The company was nationalized in 1958 and now employs 1500 people who annually mass-produce an estimated seven million pairs of inexpensive scissors that retail for an average of US$4 each.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] In the late 14th century, the English word "scissors" came into usage.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] It was derived from the Old French word *cisoires*, which referred to shears.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] There are several historically important scissor-producing regions in France: Haute-Marne in Nogent-en Bassigny, Châtellereault, Thiers and Rouen.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] These towns, like many other scissor-producing communities, began with sabre, sword and bayonet production, which transitioned to scissors and other blades in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Thiers, in the Puy-de-Dôme department of Auvergne, remains an important centre of scissor and cutlery production.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] It is home to both the Musée de la Coutellerie, which showcases the town's 800-year history of blade-making, as well as Coutellia, an industry tradeshow that advertises itself as one of the largest annual gatherings of artisanal blade-makers in the world.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Germany was responsible for manufacturing just under 7% of global scissors exports in 2019.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Often called "The City of Blades", Solingen, in North Rhine-Westphalia, has been a center for the manufacturing of scissors since medieval times.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] At the end of the 18th century it's estimated that there were over 300 scissorsmiths in Solingen.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] In 1995 the City of Solingen passed The Solingen Ordinance, an update to a 1930s law that decreed "Made in Solingen" stamps could only be applied to products almost entirely manufactured in the old industrial area of Solingen.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] In 2019 this applied to approximately 150 companies making high-quality blades of all kinds, including scissors.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Friedrich Herder, founded in Solingen in 1727, is one of the oldest scissors manufacturers still operating in Germany.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Premana, in Lecco Province, has its origins in ironworks and knife manufacturing beginning in the 16th century.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] In 1900 there were ten scissor manufacturing workshops, 20 in 1952 and 48 by 1960.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Today, Consorzio Premax, an industrial partnership, organizes over 60 local companies involved in the manufacture of scissors for global markets.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] In 2019 Italy exported 3.5% of scissors manufactured globally.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] One of the oldest Premanese scissor manufacturing firms still in operation is Sanelli Ambrogio, which was founded in 1869.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Scissormaking in Japan evolved from sword making in the 14th century.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Seki, in Gifu Prefecture, was a renowned center of swordmaking beginning in the 1200s.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] After citizens were no longer permitted to carry swords, the city's blacksmiths turned to making scissors and knives.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] There are many specialized types of Japanese scissors, but sewing scissors were introduced by American Commodore Matthew Perry from the United States in 1854.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The Sasuke workshop in Sakai City south of Osaka is run by Yasuhiro Hirakawa, a 5th generation scissorsmith.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The company has been in operation since 1867.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Yasuhiro Hirakawa is the last traditional scissormaker in Japan, making scissors in the traditional style where the blades are believed to be thinner, lighter and sharper than European scissors.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] In 2018 he was profiled in a documentary that featured a pair of his bonsai snips which retailed for US$35,000.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] In Solsona, Spain, scissor manufacturing began in the 16th century.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] At the industry's peak in the 18th century there were 24 workshops, organized as the Guild of Saint Eligius, the patron saint of knife makers.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] By the mid-1980s there were only two, and by 2021, Pallarès Solsona, founded in 1917 by Lluìs and Carles Pallarès Canal, and still family-operated, was the town's sole remaining artisanal scissor manufacturer.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Sheffield was home to the first mass production of scissors beginning in 1761.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] By the 19th century there were an estimated 60 steel scissor companies in Sheffield.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] However, since the 1980s, industry globalization and a shift towards cheaper, mass-produced scissors created price deflation that many artisanal manufacturers could not compete with.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The Sheffield scissor industry consisted of just two local companies in 2021.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The two remaining Sheffield scissor manufacturers are William Whiteley, founded in 1760, and Ernest Wright, which was established in 1902.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Both now focus on high-end/niche crafting of "products for life" rather than mass production.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Between these two firms it is estimated that there are no more than ten "putter-togetherers" or "putters" who are the master-trained craftspeople responsible for high quality Sheffield scissor assembly.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] In 2020, Ernest Wright was recognized with the Award for Endangered Crafts by the British Heritage Crafts Association.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] There are two varieties of left-handed scissors.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Many common left-handed scissors (often called "semi"-left-handed scissors) simply have reversed finger grips.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] The blades open and close as with right-handed scissors, so that users tend to pull the blades apart as they are cutting.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] This can be challenging for craftspeople as the blades still obscure the cut.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] "True" left-handed scissors have both reversed finger grips and reversed blade layout, like mirror images of right-handed scissors.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] A left-handed person accustomed to using semi-left handed scissors may find using true left-handed scissors difficult at first, as they may have learned to rely heavily on the strength of their thumb to pull the blades apart vs. pushing the blades together in order to cut.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Some scissors are marketed as ambidextrous.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] These have symmetric handles so there is no distinction between the thumb and finger handles, and have very strong pivots so that the blades rotate without any lateral give.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] However, most "ambidextrous" scissors are in fact still right-handed in that the upper blade is on the right, and hence is on the outside when held in the right hand.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] Even if they cut successfully, the blade orientation will block the view of the cutting line for a left-handed person.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] True ambidextrous scissors are possible if the blades are double-edged and one handle is swung all the way around (to almost 360 degrees) so that what were the backs of the blades become the new cutting edges.
[src:aesthetic/scissor] U.S. patent 3,978,584 was awarded for true ambidextrous scissors.
